{"id": "3347", "revid": "283556", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3347", "title": "Ranger", "text": "This page describes the Ranger class in &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition\"&gt;Enhanced Editions&lt;/a&gt; and in .\nIntroduction.\nRangers are devoted to protecting nature and their own survival whilst doing their duty. Because of that, they must be strong, wise, tough and agile to survive.\nIn gameplay, they can use nearly every weapon and piece of armor, just like the &lt;a href=\"fighter\"&gt;fighter&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;, but unlike fighters, they can only invest a maximum of two points into &lt;a href=\"Weapon%20Proficiency\"&gt;weapon proficiency&lt;/a&gt;, with the exception of bows and crossbows for &lt;a href=\"Ranger%23Archer\"&gt;Archer&lt;/a&gt;. Rangers have racial enemies, plus &lt;a href=\"Charm%20Animal\"&gt;charm animal/mammal&lt;/a&gt; and stealth as special abilities.\nBecause they have &lt;a href=\"Strength\"&gt;Strength&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dexterity\"&gt;Dexterity&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Wisdom\"&gt;Wisdom&lt;/a&gt; as their primary ability scores, and have a high minimum in each of them, rangers have the tendency to get 90 or more ability scores easily.\nIf a ranger protagonist falls below 7\u00a0&lt;a href=\"reputation\"&gt;reputation&lt;/a&gt; (or due to possible story-related reasons at the end of BG2(EE)), they will become a Fallen Ranger, which is a ranger without the special abilities, and they will lose a lot of experience points. Only in \"Shadows of Amn\" campaign at the end of &lt;a href=\"Ranger-Protector%20of%20the%20Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Ranger-Protector of the Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt;, can they become normal rangers once more. Multi and dual-classed rangers can't fall, and neither can ranger &lt;a href=\"companions\"&gt;companions&lt;/a&gt; (but since all ranger companions have good &lt;a href=\"alignment\"&gt;alignment&lt;/a&gt;, they will start leaving the party at low reputation). \n&lt;a href=\"Human\"&gt;Human&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"elf\"&gt;elves&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"half-elf\"&gt;half-elves&lt;/a&gt; may become rangers. \nThe only multi-/dual-class option for rangers is with &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;.\nCharacter abilities table.\nDuring character creation, rolls below the minimum value for the class will be increased to that value. This table uses the values for &lt;a href=\"Human\"&gt;Human&lt;/a&gt;, other Races have modified ability scores.\n^ Rangers have access to percentile Strength.\nSpecial abilities of the ranger.\nRacial enemy.\nRangers tend to focus on a particular enemy race, gaining +4 bonus to hit and damage rolls versus the racial enemy. Some of these are not available in original Baldur's Gate or Tales of the Sword Coast and were added when Shadows of Amn and Throne of Bhaal were released. Several low-level groups are only available in the first Baldur's Gate games. When importing a character from BG1 into BG2, you can choose a new racial enemy when you start a new game. The player chooses one of the creature types listed below.\n &lt;a href=\"Carrion%20Crawler\"&gt;Carrion Crawler&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ettercap\"&gt;Ettercap&lt;/a&gt;, , , , &lt;a href=\"Hobgoblin\"&gt;Hobgoblin&lt;/a&gt;, , , , , &lt;a href=\"Trolls\"&gt;Troll&lt;/a&gt;, , , , , \n &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;Beholder&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Carrion%20Crawler\"&gt;Carrion Crawler&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Demon\"&gt;Demonic Fell Creature&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dragon\"&gt;Dragon&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Elemental\"&gt;Elemental&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ettercap\"&gt;Ettercap&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Hamadryad\"&gt;Fairy&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Djinni\"&gt;Genie&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ghoul\"&gt;Ghoul&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Gibberling\"&gt;Gibberling&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Golem\"&gt;Golem&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Gnoll\"&gt;Gnoll&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Hobgoblin\"&gt;Hobgoblin&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Imp\"&gt;Imp&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Kobold\"&gt;Kobold&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Kuo-Toa\"&gt;Kuo-Toa&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Lich\"&gt;Lich&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Lycanthrope\"&gt;Lycanthrope&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Mephit\"&gt;Mephit&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Mind%20Flayer\"&gt;Mind Flayer&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ogre\"&gt;Ogre&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Orc\"&gt;Orc&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Otyugh\"&gt;Otyugh&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Rakshasa\"&gt;Rakshasa&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Sahuagin\"&gt;Sahuagin&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shadow\"&gt;Shadow&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Skeleton\"&gt;Skeleton&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Slime\"&gt;Slime&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spiders\"&gt;Spider&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Trolls\"&gt;Troll&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Umber%20Hulk\"&gt;Umber Hulk&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Vampire\"&gt;Vampire&lt;/a&gt;\nCharm animal.\nRangers can &lt;a href=\"Charm%20Animal\"&gt;charm animals&lt;/a&gt; to prevent fights or to gain advantages, starting from level 3.\n&lt;a href=\"Stealth\"&gt;Stealth&lt;/a&gt;.\nRangers can &lt;a href=\"Stealth\"&gt;Hide In Shadows&lt;/a&gt; when not wearing heavy armor. Rangers get a bonus to their stealth skills based on level, starting at +15 for both Move Silently and Hide In Shadows at level 1 (maxing out at 99 for both at level 13). These skills are further modified by race selection, &lt;a href=\"dexterity\"&gt;dexterity&lt;/a&gt; score, and increase with level. With the exception of Stalkers, Rangers may not Backstab like &lt;a href=\"Thief\"&gt;thieves&lt;/a&gt;, but they still receive the -4 &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; bonus when they strike while hidden.\n&lt;a href=\"Druid%23Druid%20spells\"&gt;Druid spells&lt;/a&gt;.\nRangers unlock druid spells at level 8, may learn up to spell level 3. The caster level for these spells is calculated as 7 levels less than the current Ranger level, but maxes out at level 9 in classic versions. In the Enhanced Editions, the caster level continues to increase normally with the penalty (up to a max of 27 at level 34). Lower caster level means that many spell effects are weaker or last a shorter duration, and they can more easily be &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;dispelled&lt;/a&gt;.\nSingle class rangers do not gain &lt;a href=\"wisdom\"&gt;wisdom&lt;/a&gt; based bonus spell slots; cleric &amp; ranger combinations gain additional slots like single class clerics. In Classic Versions, rangers multi or dual with cleric may learn lv4+ druid spells when the higher spell level slots are unlocked by cleric. In the Enhanced Edition, this has been turned into an option in the external configuration file called \"baldur.lua\". For more information, see the &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20/%20Ranger\"&gt;Cleric / Ranger&lt;/a&gt; page.\nClass Kits.\nRanger.\nThe ranger is a warrior and a woodsman who is skilled with weapons and is knowledgeable in the ways of the forest. The Ranger often protects and guides lost travelers and honest peasant-folk. A Ranger needs to be strong and wise to the ways of nature to live a full life.\nClass features:\nGameplay\n&lt;a href=\"Archer\"&gt;Archer&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Archer is the epitome of skill with the bow - the ultimate marksman, able to make almost any shot, no matter how difficult. To become so skilled with the bow, the Archer has had to sacrifice some of the proficiency with melee weapons and armor.\u00a0\nAdvantages:\u00a0\nDisadvantages:\u00a0\nGameplay\n&lt;a href=\"Stalker\"&gt;Stalker&lt;/a&gt;.\nStalkers serve as covert intelligence-gatherers, comfortable in both wilderness and urban settings. They are spies, informants, and interrogators, and their mastery of &lt;a href=\"Stealth\"&gt;stealth&lt;/a&gt; makes them deadly opponents.\u00a0\nAdvantages:\u00a0\nDisadvantages:\u00a0\nGameplay\n&lt;a href=\"Beast%20Master\"&gt;Beast Master&lt;/a&gt;.\nBeast Masters are wanderers and are not comfortable in civilized lands. Therefore, they maintain a natural affinity for animals; who are the Beast Masters' friends and comrades-in-arms, and the Beast Masters have a limited form of telepathic communication with the animals.\u00a0\nAdvantages:\u00a0\nDisadvantages:\u00a0\nGameplay\n&lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class abilities&lt;/a&gt;.\nHigh level class abilities are added in expansion. For all warrior classes and\u00a0Monks, the pool of abilities consist of abilities which can be accessed from the special abilities menu. These HLAs are available once they reach levels beyond 3,000,000 &lt;a href=\"Experience%20Tables\"&gt;xp&lt;/a&gt;, exact level varies by class.\n&lt;a href=\"Stronghold\"&gt;Stronghold&lt;/a&gt;.\nA Protagonist ranger serves as &lt;a href=\"Ranger-Protector%20of%20the%20Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Ranger-Protector of the Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt; once the &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20the%20deaths%20in%20the%20Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Investigate the deaths in the Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt; side quest is completed.\nCreative origins.\nThe ranger was primarily based on the exiled king , and the of mythos, as warriors who use tracking and other wilderness skills to hunt down their enemies. The \"AD&amp;D\" second edition handbook mentions several other inspirations from myth and legend, such as , , the huntresses , and the Greek hero .\nAlthough it is commonly thought that the ranger character &lt;a href=\"Drizzt%20Do%27Urden\"&gt;Drizzt Do'Urden&lt;/a&gt; may also have influenced the development of the class, particularly with regard to the second edition inclusion of the ability to fight with two weapons, this notion has been rejected by the lead designer of that rule set, David \"Zeb\" Cook, and the lack of provision for players to be able to emulate Drizzt using the ranger class as it appears in the PHB seems to support his assertion. More likely, the Drizzt character was influenced by \"Unearthed Arcana\", which introduced the drow as a player character race and contained somewhat ambiguous wording that allowed them to use a secondary weapon not normally permitted in \"AD&amp;D\". Drizzt appeared as a first edition character in the 1988 release \"FR5 \". Interestingly, few \"AD&amp;D\" computer games based on the second edition rule set included provision for fighting with two weapons, and those that did seem to have not have included the ranger class ability (most notably, \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\" and \"&lt;a href=\"Icewind%20Dale\"&gt;Icewind Dale&lt;/a&gt;\" , which provided rangers with an extra attack when not using a shield.)\nOther notable rangers in the literature of \"Dungeons &amp; Dragons\" include Hank from the , King Tristan Kendrick from Forgotten Realms, and Ren from Pool of Radiance.\nAchievements.\nOathbreaker BG1.\nBecome a Fallen Paladin or a Fallen Ranger during or .\nOathbreaker BG2.\nBecome a Fallen Paladin or a Fallen Ranger during .\nCabin In the Woods.\nAcquire the ranger stronghold during .\nEpic Warrior.\nReach level 30 with a Fighter, Ranger, Paladin, Monk, or Barbarian during .\nGameplay (community).\n~Write your insights below, different from the Gameplay section above, you may use your signatures here,\u00a0~\nAlignment exploits with certain items.\nDespite the alignment limitation at character creation, it must be noted that it's possible for a party to have a non-Fallen evil Ranger in BG(EE) and Siege of Dragonspear, as the &lt;a href=\"Helmet%20of%20Opposite%20Alignment\"&gt;Helmet of Opposite Alignment&lt;/a&gt; does not cause Rangers to fall. This can be of particular interest to &lt;a href=\"Beast%20Master\"&gt;Beast Masters&lt;/a&gt;, whose &lt;a href=\"Find%20Familiar\"&gt;familiar&lt;/a&gt; choice is determined by their alignment, or any Ranger who would like to make use of the &lt;a href=\"Cornugon%27s%20Revenge\"&gt;Cornugon's Revenge&lt;/a&gt; armor during SoD. Moreover, although of little practical use to most players, it's also possible to keep said Ranger as evil by skipping the Shadows of Amn portion of BG2(EE) and importing the BG(EE) character with the Helmet of Opposite Alignment straight into Throne of Bhaal (as the helmet still exists in the code and ToB doesn't remove items from the player's party). Finally, it's also possible to keep a Ranger as evil after removing the Helmet of Opposite Alignment through the use of &lt;a href=\"exploits\"&gt;exploits&lt;/a&gt; (check the Helmet of Opposite Alignment section), which allows the Ranger to use many non-good or evil-exclusive items when they reach BG2(EE), such as the &lt;a href=\"Human%20Flesh\"&gt;Human Flesh&lt;/a&gt; armor, the &lt;a href=\"Silver%20Dragon%20Scale\"&gt;Silver Dragon Scale&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"The%20Visage\"&gt;The Visage&lt;/a&gt;. "}
{"id": "6681", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6681", "title": "Ranger-Protector of the Umar Hills", "text": "Ranger-Protector of the Umar Hills is a set of three linked &lt;a href=\"stronghold\"&gt;stronghold&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"quests\"&gt;quests&lt;/a&gt; that can be unlocked if &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; is a &lt;a href=\"Ranger\"&gt;Ranger&lt;/a&gt;.\nAcquisition.\nAfter completing the &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20the%20Deaths%20in%20the%20Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Investigate the Deaths in the Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt; quest, &lt;a href=\"Minister%20Lloyd\"&gt;Minister Lloyd&lt;/a&gt; offers &lt;a href=\"Merella\"&gt;Merella's&lt;/a&gt; position to become the new Ranger-Protector for the &lt;a href=\"Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt;. If accepted, Gorion's Ward is now the owner of Merella's &lt;a href=\"Ranger%20Cabin\"&gt;Ranger Cabin&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0and all that it contains. Go to the cabin and read the &lt;a href=\"Note%20from%20Imnesvale\"&gt;Note from Imnesvale&lt;/a&gt; left for you by the grateful townsfolk of &lt;a href=\"Imnesvale\"&gt;Imnesvale&lt;/a&gt;. Also &lt;a href=\"Ranger%20Cabin%23Ranger%20Stronghold\"&gt;check the containers&lt;/a&gt; for weapons and ammunition (both magical and mundane), as well as a few potions.\nFallen Rangers.\nIf Gorion's Ward has become a &lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Fallen Ranger&lt;/a&gt;, you will still be offered the position, and successful completion of all three of these quests results in Ranger status being restored by Mielikki.\nQuest #1: Lord Tombelthen.\nThe first quest starts when you camp outside of your Cabin, or you return to the Umar Hills after having been gone from the area for some time.\nMairyn.\n&lt;a href=\"Mairyn\"&gt;Mairyn the Forest Spirit&lt;/a&gt;, one of the fae residents of the region, appears and pleads with the party to stop a party of humans who are destroying the forest by tearing down trees and ripping open the earth near the Shadow Portal. She will be surprised if you ask about a reward; so either accept or deny her plea.\nLord Tombelthen.\nThe group is located southwest of the Altar. When the party approaches, they encounter &lt;a href=\"Lord%20Igen%20Tombelthen\"&gt;Lord Igen Tombelthen&lt;/a&gt;, who, if given the chance, will explain that he is looking for a cache of Mithral hidden in the area by an ancestor of his, and he refuses to leave without it. He gives you a &lt;a href=\"Tombelthen%27s%20Journal%20%28first%20half%29\"&gt;torn journal&lt;/a&gt; containing information about the location of the mithral.\nFinding the Mithral.\nThe second half of &lt;a href=\"Tombelthen%27s%20Journal%20%28second%20half%29\"&gt;Tombelthen's Journal&lt;/a&gt; that the party may have already found in the &lt;a href=\"Ruined%20Temple\"&gt;Ruined Temple&lt;/a&gt; informs the player where the Mithral is located. However, it can also be found by exploring the area east of Lord Tombelthen's location, where a number of &lt;a href=\"Skeleton\"&gt;Skeleton&lt;/a&gt;s led by a &lt;a href=\"Skeleton%20Warrior\"&gt;Skeleton Warrior&lt;/a&gt; (4000 &lt;a href=\"XP\"&gt;XP&lt;/a&gt;) surround a rock outcropping. Once the undead are dealt with, the &lt;a href=\"Mithral%20Medallion\"&gt;Mithral Medallion&lt;/a&gt; can be found hidden in a crack in the rock.\nOutcomes.\nUpon returning to Lord Tombelthen he offers for the medallion. The player has several options:\nNote that after you give the medallion you can still kill Lord Tombelthen (and possibly his &lt;a href=\"Tamorlin%20%28Temple%20Ruins%29\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt;) as he's trying to leave the game which gets you the 6,000 kill XP, his gear, and the medallion back.\nReward.\nReturn to the Ranger Cabin, where Mairyn is waiting outside. Upon confirming their departure or deaths to Mairyn, the party splits 21500 XP.\nQuest #2: Orog Attack.\nThree to four days after completing the previous quest, &lt;a href=\"Delon\"&gt;Delon&lt;/a&gt; approaches the party looking for help, which begins this quest. He begs you return to Imnesvale and talk to Minister Lloyd. Once the party is notified, they have three days to return to Imnesvale and speak with Minister Lloyd before they fail this quest.\nMinister Lloyd explains that a number of &lt;a href=\"%23Trivia\"&gt;t&lt;/a&gt; raiders have attacked, and they have pinned &lt;a href=\"Madulf\"&gt;Madulf&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Atta\"&gt;Atta&lt;/a&gt;, one of the village's shepherd boys, inside a nearby &lt;a href=\"Umar%20Cave\"&gt;cave&lt;/a&gt;. The party will need to dispatch the raiders that include several &lt;a href=\"Orog\"&gt;Orog&lt;/a&gt;s backed by &lt;a href=\"Orc%20Archer%20%28Umar%20Hills%E2%80%94Ranger%29\"&gt;Orc Archers&lt;/a&gt;. The orog leader has &lt;a href=\"Studded%20Leather%20Armor%20%2B2\"&gt;Studded Leather Armor +2&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword%20%2B1\"&gt;Bastard Sword +1&lt;/a&gt;, and an item of &lt;a href=\"Random%20treasure%23Well-off%20treasure\"&gt;well-off random treasure&lt;/a&gt;. After the battle, check on Madulf and Atta inside the cave.\nThe party will receive 21750 XP for speaking to Madulf, and another 25000 XP when they return to Minister Lloyd and tell him the story that Madulf shares with them.\nQuest #3: Umar the Witch.\nFour days after the completion of the second Ranger Stronghold quest, you will again meet Delon. He asks you to return to the Umar Hills again and speak to Minister Lloyd. This time, the &lt;a href=\"Umar\"&gt;Umar Witch&lt;/a&gt; has returned!\nThe finale of this quest sees the party directed to the entrance of the Shadow Dungeon in the Temple Ruins, where Mairyn appears and begs them to do something about the witch, \"who has threatened your village... her dark and foul magics have also begun to poison the woodland!\" Enter the Temple (AR1401) once again to seek out, find and destroy Umar.\nUmar's battle party is as follows:\nDepending on the PC's experience level at the time of this encounter, there will be additional allied creatures to support Umar. \nUpon her death (4000 XP), loot her for a &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Lightning\"&gt;Wand of Lightning&lt;/a&gt; \"\" and other gear. Return to the surface and confirm her death to Mairyn. The party is rewarded with +1 &lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Reputation&lt;/a&gt;, 26750 XP, and a &lt;a href=\"Moon%20Dog%20Figurine\"&gt;Moon Dog Figurine&lt;/a&gt;. There's no need to go back and speak with Minister Lloyd again.\nMod content.\nMods.\nIf you are using a mod that permits you to revisit the areas of &lt;a href=\"Shadows%20of%20Amn\"&gt;Shadows of Amn&lt;/a&gt; content after reaching the extension, then you can of course also use this quest to restore your Ranger status after falling in the &lt;a href=\"Tears%20of%20Bhaal\"&gt;Tears of Bhaal tests&lt;/a&gt;. This constitutes a second way to acquire an evil Ranger in a modded game (the first, available without mods, being the use of the &lt;a href=\"Helmet%20of%20Opposite%20Alignment\"&gt;Helmet of Opposite Alignment&lt;/a&gt; in BGEE and, beyond that, the use of exploits to make the change permanent). If you plan to do this, then you would be well advised to finish the &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20the%20Deaths%20in%20the%20Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Investigate the Deaths in the Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt; quest during the Shadows of Amn part of the game, but then not report your success to the mayor. This will allow you to recruit &lt;a href=\"Mazzy%20Fentan\"&gt;Mazzy&lt;/a&gt; (who would be gone from her prison cell if you delayed the quest until ), while avoiding getting into trouble with the timers that the stronghold quest lies under."}
