{"id": "31033", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=31033", "title": "Rashad", "text": "Rashad was a healer, in the employ of &lt;a href=\"Duke%20Eltan\"&gt;Duke Eltan&lt;/a&gt;, one of the Grand Dukes of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. Either he was a doppelganger in the employ of &lt;a href=\"Sarevok%20Anchev\"&gt;Sarevok&lt;/a&gt; all along, or at some point the original Rashad was killed and replaced by one. As a part of the plot of Sarevok to destabilize the city so he could take control, Rashad's job was to slowly poison Eltan, although outwardly giving the appearance of a natural sickness, and thereby render Eltan unfit to command - with a view that his eventual death should appear natural, until then keeping him alive so that orders could be given in his name. The plot was uncovered, and Rashad - like his master - met his death at the hand of &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt;.\nFollowing the dialogue, Rashad will shapeshift into his true &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Doppelganger\"&gt;Greater Doppelganger&lt;/a&gt; form."}
{"id": "3780", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3780", "title": "Rashad's Talon", "text": "Rashad's Talon (Rashad's Talon +2 in-game), also known as Scimitar +2, is a &lt;a href=\"Scimitar\"&gt;Scimitar&lt;/a&gt; with a +2 &lt;a href=\"enchantment\"&gt;enchantment&lt;/a&gt;. This weapon is lighter, faster, and offers +2 bonus to damage and &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; compared to its ordinary analogue. \u00a0Due to its magical nature it can harm enemies immune to normal weapons."}
{"id": "20089", "revid": "978785", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20089", "title": "Rashad's Talon +2", "text": ""}
{"id": "7387", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7387", "title": "Rashemen", "text": "Rashemen is matriarchal magocracy in the east &lt;a href=\"Faer%C3%BBn\"&gt;Faer\u00fbn&lt;/a&gt; bordered to the south by &lt;a href=\"Thay\"&gt;Thay&lt;/a&gt;. The country is famous for its Witches, female &lt;a href=\"Mage\"&gt;spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; who serve as leaders of communities and the nation. They form a council that elects the Iron Lord, the nominal leader of the nation, serve as his counselours and have to power to replace him if needed.\nRashemen has a strong tradition of &lt;a href=\"Berserker\"&gt;Berserker&lt;/a&gt; warriors, which are organized into lodges or fangs. They put valor and bravery above all, but are required to be able to control their rage at all times. Dajemma was a type of coming-of-age tradition for young Rashemi men to travel to foreign lands to see and understand more of the world. A young man sometimes traveled with a witch companion, called a wychlaran.\nRashemi people are at odds with neighbouring &lt;a href=\"Thay\"&gt;Thay&lt;/a&gt;, as the &lt;a href=\"Red%20Wizards%20of%20Thay\"&gt;Red Wizards of Thay&lt;/a&gt; want to conquer the land and enslave its people.\n&lt;a href=\"Minsc\"&gt;Minsc&lt;/a&gt; travels on dajemma with his witch &lt;a href=\"Dynaheir\"&gt;Dynaheir&lt;/a&gt;, whom he was expected to serve faithfully. The Thayan-Rashemi relations are reflected in &lt;a href=\"Edwin%20Odesseiron\"&gt;Edwin Odesseiron&lt;/a&gt;'s plot to kill Dynaheir and the constant antagonizing between him and Minsc."}
{"id": "19681", "revid": "4896558", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=19681", "title": "Rat", "text": "Rat is a hostile or non-hostile animal. They can be found hostile as one if not the first creature to kill as a part of the &lt;a href=\"Reevor%27s%20Storehouse\"&gt;Reevor's Storehouse&lt;/a&gt; quest during &lt;a href=\"Prologue\"&gt;Prologue&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep%20Storehouse\"&gt;Candlekeep Storehouse&lt;/a&gt;. They can also be found non-hostile in &lt;a href=\"Beregost%20Cave\"&gt;Beregost Cave&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Nashkel%20Mines\"&gt;Nashkel Mines&lt;/a&gt;.\nRat form via Cloak of the Sewers.\nIn the \"Rat\" form, gained through the &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20the%20Sewers\"&gt;Cloak of the Sewers&lt;/a&gt;, the polymorphed character obtains the following stats:"}
{"id": "23925", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=23925", "title": "Ratchild", "text": "Ratchild is the leader of a tribe of a dozen &lt;a href=\"Kobold\"&gt;Kobold&lt;/a&gt;s living in the &lt;a href=\"sewers\"&gt;sewers&lt;/a&gt; beneath &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. Upon encountering &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and party, he will summon his &lt;a href=\"Kobold%20Commando\"&gt;commandos&lt;/a&gt; to attack them. There is no way to negotiate with him.\nDialogue.\nRatchild will engage the party in dialogue as soon as they enter his line of sight.\n\"I am Ratchild! I destroy all those who oppose my people! Feel the wrath of Ratchild: Feel my wrath and tremble!\"\n\"You underestimate Ratchild! You and your friends will pay for underestimation. Yip yip yip!\"\n\"My people are rulers of the deeps. Where your peoples wastes are sent, that where we thrive. Ratchild's tribe is stronger than all others. Ratchild's tribe trained to beat anyone. ANYONE. No one can stand up to Ratchild and tribe!\"\n\"You underestimate Ratchild. Many have done so. Even Harpers have done so. All have felt Ratchild's wrath!\"\n\"You mock Ratchild! No one mocks Ratchild and lives! Yip, yip yip!\"\nCombat.\nUpon ending the dialogue, Ratchild will summon 11 Kobold Commandos scattered throughout the passageways connected to the central chamber where he is located. Two in particular will spawn behind the character he is speaking to. Not all of the commandos will be visible from the start of the fight, but their locations will become apparent once the party fully enters the chamber.\nRatchild himself is not much of a threat alone, but he \"is\" able to cast spells. His repertoire includes particularly annoying spells such as &lt;a href=\"Hold%20Person%20%28priest%29\"&gt;Hold Person&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Rigid%20Thinking\"&gt;Rigid Thinking&lt;/a&gt;. The real challenge in the battle, however, comes from his tribe's sheer numbers and the fact your party is surrounded - Ratchild's magic wouldn't be near as much of a problem if the party could actually focus on attacking him without getting shot by eleven &lt;a href=\"Arrow%20of%20Fire\"&gt;Arrows of Fire&lt;/a&gt; at once. It may be a good idea to have more fragile members of the party wait further up the passage, because they can easily be killed if two or more of the Kobolds target any of them at once."}
{"id": "6880", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6880", "title": "Rattell", "text": "Rattell is a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Thieves\"&gt;Shadow Thief&lt;/a&gt; who will replace &lt;a href=\"Gorch\"&gt;Gorch&lt;/a&gt; as the new purveyor of goods behind the counter in &lt;a href=\"Mae%27Var\"&gt;Mae'Var's&lt;/a&gt; former guildhall, now referred to as &lt;a href=\"Mae%27Var%27s%20Guildhall\"&gt;Gorion's Ward's Guildhall&lt;/a&gt;, if &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; is a thief and has undertaken the &lt;a href=\"Thieves%27%20Guild%20Stronghold\"&gt;Thieves' Guild Stronghold&lt;/a&gt; quest. He has his own stock that's comprised primarily of mundane weapons along with some mage scrolls. He also sells a few &lt;a href=\"Lesser%20Restoration\"&gt;Lesser Restoration&lt;/a&gt; scrolls.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Rogue%20Rebalancing\"&gt;Rogue Rebalancing&lt;/a&gt; Mod alters Rattell's stock a bit, including mod only rogue-centric wares and unique items, some not found in the unmodded game."}
{"id": "6810", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6810", "title": "Ravager", "text": "Ravager +4 is an enchanted halberd. It deals 1d10 +4 points of &lt;a href=\"Piercing%20damage\"&gt;Piercing damage&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Slashing%20damage\"&gt;Slashing damage&lt;/a&gt;, it has -4 &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; bonus, a speed factor of 5 and it weighs 12 lbs. This can also be used to cast &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Fear\"&gt;Cloak of Fear&lt;/a&gt; on the wielder two times each day. \nThis item appears in and .\nThis weapon can be found in the &lt;a href=\"Marching%20Mountains\"&gt;Marching Mountains&lt;/a&gt;. It's dropped by the Fire Elemental Prince &lt;a href=\"Imix\"&gt;Imix&lt;/a&gt;, who can be found in the second part of Yaga-Shura's Temple. The Ravager +6 (upgraded!) can be acquired in as a reward item after defeating the &lt;a href=\"Bhaalspawn\"&gt;Bhaalspawn&lt;/a&gt; in Tier 4 - Battle 4 (Battle 19).\nThis weapon can be upgraded by &lt;a href=\"Cespenar\"&gt;Cespenar&lt;/a&gt;, which requires some gold and the &lt;a href=\"Serpent%20Shaft\"&gt;Serpent Shaft&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Ravager halberd should not be confused with The Ravager, the Fifth Challenge in the &lt;a href=\"Pocket%20Plane\"&gt;Pocket Plane&lt;/a&gt;.\nUpgraded.\nRavager +6 deals now 1d10 +6 points of damage and it has -6 &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; bonus. The weapons weighs 10 lbs and it has a speed factor of 3. The weapon has two combat abilities: it can deal 3-18 points with each hit if the target fails a save vs. poison and it can decapitate an opponent with 10% chance, for which no saving throw can be made. The decapitation instant-kills most normal enemies, most bosses are immune to it. In this state, Ravager is the most powerful halberd available and a very powerful weapon."}
