{"id": "49691", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49691", "title": "Pimlico", "text": "Pimlico is a wealthy nobleman residing in the &lt;a href=\"Pimlico%20Estate\"&gt;Pimlico Estate&lt;/a&gt; located in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20District\"&gt;Temple District&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nPimlico is collector or rare books, tomes and papers. The party may interact with him as part of the &lt;a href=\"Help%20Korgan%20Recover%20the%20Book%20of%20Kaza\"&gt;Help Korgan Recover the Book of Kaza&lt;/a&gt; questline. Pimlico will pay a reward to whoever gets him &lt;a href=\"The%20Book%20of%20Kaza\"&gt;The Book of Kaza&lt;/a&gt; first.\nOnce the party has recruited &lt;a href=\"Korgan%20Bloodaxe\"&gt;Korgan Bloodaxe&lt;/a&gt; and agreed to take on the questline, there is an opportunity to visit Pimlico in the estate and have dialogue. After a certain event in the quest, Pimlico cannot be spoken to again due to deathly circumstances. So, if the party wished to converse with Pimlico, do so before setting off to the &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Tombs\"&gt;Lower Tombs&lt;/a&gt; to find the tome. He'll be silent after that."}
{"id": "13568", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13568", "title": "Pimlico Estate", "text": "The Pimlico Estate is a noble's mansion in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Temple%20District\"&gt;Temple District&lt;/a&gt;. Except for a specific quest (below) the building cannot be entered by the party.\nGameplay.\nThis building can only be entered if the party has recruited &lt;a href=\"Korgan%20Bloodaxe\"&gt;Korgan Bloodaxe&lt;/a&gt; and accepted the &lt;a href=\"Help%20Korgan%20Recover%20the%20Book%20of%20Kaza\"&gt;Help Korgan Recover the Book of Kaza&lt;/a&gt; questline. \nIf the party visits Pimlico's estate, and Korgan speaks to Pimlico about the status of his open paid job to find &lt;a href=\"The%20Book%20of%20Kaza\"&gt;The Book of Kaza&lt;/a&gt;, then some up to date information is learned. See the quest article for further information.\nContainers.\nThere are a number of shelves, tables, chests and a drawer inside the estate. Some or locked. One may be trapped. Opening these could trigger the CTALARM.bcs script - this can lead to a summoning of the city guard enforcer appearance. If spoken to, the guards within warn the player \"Don't be touchin' Mr. Pimlico's stuff! I'm watchin' ye...\"\nIndeed, there are valuables in some of these containers. Is it worth the risk to try and plunder these when the guards are watching? And the potential for a city enforcer to respond to stealing attempts in the home of the wealthy? And how will that affect Pimlico and promise to pay a reward if he finds out you attempted to steal from him? That is up to the player to decide.\nTrivia.\nThe name 'Pimlico' is from a Horse Racing Course near Baltimore Maryland. Employees of Bethesda Softworks would frequent the course to bet on the horses. Some of those software developers began working for Black Isle Studios - and did part of the game development work for Bioware. One of the developers added Pimlico as an NPC name to the game."}
{"id": "51978", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51978", "title": "Pimlico Guard", "text": "Pimlico Guard is a hired human male fighter within in the &lt;a href=\"Pimlico%20Estate\"&gt;Pimlico Estate&lt;/a&gt; located in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20District\"&gt;Temple District&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nTwo of these guards are stationed within the estate of wealthy nobleman &lt;a href=\"Pimlico\"&gt;Pimlico&lt;/a&gt;, providing security.\nIf made hostile, they will attack. These guards will also join the Amnian Guard enforcer (see &lt;a href=\"Amnian%20Legionary\"&gt;Amnian Legionary&lt;/a&gt;) if the alarm script is triggered by attempting open certain containers in the building."}
{"id": "50998", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50998", "title": "Pip", "text": "Pip is halfling butler or manservant for the &lt;a href=\"Balthis%20Estate\"&gt;Balthis Estate&lt;/a&gt;. He will intercept and greet you when you enter the estate. Unless you have a valid reason for doing so, you will be asked to leave, and the Guards in the premises will also warn that you don't have long before the authorities arrive to treat you like unlawful trespassers. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Unfinished%20Business%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%29\"&gt;Unfinished Business II&lt;/a&gt; mod for Baldur's Gate II: Shadows of Amn restores a quest, \"The Murder of Acton Balthis\", that was cut from the game according to &lt;a href=\"David%20Gaider\"&gt;David Gaider&lt;/a&gt; of Bioware. This quest is only for players who have taken &lt;a href=\"Haer%27Dalis\"&gt;Haer'Dalis&lt;/a&gt; as a companion, and who also, for some reason, have not already slain &lt;a href=\"Quataris\"&gt;Quataris&lt;/a&gt; the art dealer in &lt;a href=\"Waukeen%27s%20Promenade\"&gt;Waukeen's Promenade&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "17087", "revid": "3539497", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=17087", "title": "Pirate's Cave", "text": ""}
{"id": "49453", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49453", "title": "Pirate (Hideout)", "text": "Three of the \"Pirate-looking\" Pirates, along with the pirate mage, are found in the secret \"Pirate's Hideout\" that's accessible from inside the first floor of the &lt;a href=\"Sea%27s%20Bounty%20Tavern\"&gt;Sea's Bounty Tavern&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Docks\"&gt;Docks District&lt;/a&gt;. They've got the back of their &lt;a href=\"Pirate%20Captain\"&gt;Pirate Captain&lt;/a&gt; in protecting the hideout from unwanted intruders.\nThe \"pirates\" are equipped with &lt;a href=\"Chain%20Mail\"&gt;Chain Mail&lt;/a&gt;, swing a &lt;a href=\"Short%20Sword\"&gt;Short Sword&lt;/a&gt;, and possess twenty &lt;a href=\"Throwing%20Dagger\"&gt;Throwing Dagger&lt;/a&gt;s. The mage carries no weapon and wears no robe.\nGameplay.\nThe three pirates will use their throwing daggers in battle before engaging in melee combat with their short swords.\nThe mage will instantly cast &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Normal%20Missiles\"&gt;Protection From Normal Missiles&lt;/a&gt; when the first party member comes into sight. He will then cycle through his progression of spells, always targeting the nearest enemy, and finally switch to &lt;a href=\"fist\"&gt;fist&lt;/a&gt;s if his spells are depleted before he is killed.\nThese pirates are some of the \"generic no-name\" pirates encountered in the game that carry no gold or treasure. But there is a &lt;a href=\"Pearl%20Necklace\"&gt;Pearl Necklace&lt;/a&gt;, two &lt;a href=\"Pearl\"&gt;Pearl&lt;/a&gt;s and 1100 &lt;a href=\"GP\"&gt;GP&lt;/a&gt; in the pool that's located inside the hideout.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; makes revisions to all the Pirates in this Hideout, as follows:\n&lt;a href=\"Pirate%20Captain\"&gt;Pirate Captain&lt;/a&gt; article has more details, see the link.\nPirates X3: Each creature has a default SCS Fighter AI for improved tactical decision making and threat recognition behavior. They have 5 pips in dagger weapon proficiency, 2 pips in short sword, and 1 pip in single-weapon style. Being level 10 fighters, they have some decent skills and can hit often with their weaponry. The pirates have random SCS treasure in their inventory. \nPirate (Mage): An Enchanter Kit is assigned. With the Smarter Mages component will have a better and smarter overall arcane spell casting ability. A new set of memorized spells are assigned as well. The mage has a &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Sequencer\"&gt;Minor Sequencer&lt;/a&gt; with double &lt;a href=\"Sleep\"&gt;Sleep&lt;/a&gt; spells loaded.\nOnce hostilities begin, after a few moments (1-2 seconds) then the following contingency spells will be auto cast on self:\n&lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Normal%20Missiles\"&gt;Protection From Normal Missiles&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;. Afterwards expect a &lt;a href=\"Confusion\"&gt;Confusion&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Domination\"&gt;Domination&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Feeblemind\"&gt;Feeblemind&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Slow\"&gt;Slow&lt;/a&gt; spells, and since the mage is an enchanter, saving throws for the party will have a -2 penalty vs. Enchantment spells. If the mage is able to survive more than a few rounds, he will cast a spell every round at the party members in sight. The Minor Sequencer will be deployed as well. For some unusual reason, the mage has an innate 70% &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; rating."}
{"id": "49448", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49448", "title": "Pirate (Vulgar Monkey)", "text": "This Pirate is found inside the &lt;a href=\"The%20Vulgar%20Monkey\"&gt;The Vulgar Monkey&lt;/a&gt; which is located on the island of &lt;a href=\"Brynnlaw\"&gt;Brynnlaw&lt;/a&gt;. He is sitting at a table with his back to the bar. His appearance is that of a commoner and this may belial his true personna. Killing him will not harm your reputation and he carries an &lt;a href=\"Emerald\"&gt;Emerald&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "49450", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49450", "title": "Pirate Captain", "text": "The Pirate Captain is found in the secret \"Pirate's Hideout\" that's accessible from inside the first floor of the &lt;a href=\"Sea%27s%20Bounty%20Tavern\"&gt;Sea's Bounty Tavern&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Docks\"&gt;Docks District&lt;/a&gt;. He's backed by four fellow &lt;a href=\"Pirate%20%28Hideout%29\"&gt;pirates&lt;/a&gt;, one of which is a mage.\nThe captain swings a &lt;a href=\"Long%20Sword%20%2B1\"&gt;Long Sword +1&lt;/a&gt; in battle (although the poor sod is only equipped with &lt;a href=\"Leather%20Armor\"&gt;Leather Armor&lt;/a&gt;) and as 16th level pirate, he has a high &lt;a href=\"hit%20point\"&gt;hit point&lt;/a&gt; value (114) and gives up 6000 &lt;a href=\"XP\"&gt;XP&lt;/a&gt; when killed.\nThis pirate is one of the \"generic no-name\" pirates encountered in the game that carries no gold or treasure. But there is a &lt;a href=\"Pearl%20Necklace\"&gt;Pearl Necklace&lt;/a&gt;, two &lt;a href=\"Pearl\"&gt;Pearl&lt;/a&gt;s and 1100 &lt;a href=\"GP\"&gt;GP&lt;/a&gt; in the pool that's located inside the hideout.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod improves the AI for these pirates and alters their weapon proficiencies and attack tactics. Overall, they are a more formidable challenge. The Pirate Captain gas 5 pips and is a grandmaster in long sword weapon proficiency, as well as 2 pips in single weapon fighting style. Expect a very good sword slashing melee fighter in combat. His adjusted THAC0 is 1, and now has 3 &lt;a href=\"Attacks%20per%20round\"&gt;Attacks per round&lt;/a&gt;, dealing +5 slashing damage. The Captain has some SCS random treasure in his inventory."}
{"id": "51239", "revid": "25646820", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51239", "title": "Pirate Door Guard", "text": "Pirate Door Guard is a fighter class pirate posted at the doorway to &lt;a href=\"Desharik%27s%20Estate\"&gt;Desharik's Estate&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Brynnlaw\"&gt;Brynnlaw&lt;/a&gt;. The only way to get inside the Estate is if this doorman allows passage. The door cannot be lock picked, nor is there a key, and the door cannot be opened with a &lt;a href=\"Knock\"&gt;Knock&lt;/a&gt; spell or forced.\nGameplay.\nWhen the party speaks to the guard (and they should), he'll basically say that you can't see the Pirate Lord &lt;a href=\"Desharik\"&gt;Desharik&lt;/a&gt; without an appointment. However, if you have certain information gained as part of the &lt;a href=\"Getting%20inside%20the%20asylum\"&gt;Getting inside the asylum&lt;/a&gt; quest, then more dialogue options will open up. All in all, you can drop a few names, or just bribe the guard, and he'll let the party in. The guard really never threatens the party or isn't open to answering how to get inside to see the Pirate Lord. \nIf the party decides to commit murder on the streets of Brynnlaw, and slay this guard - then go ahead and do so. Role play in the manner desired. On the other hand, the guard has the GPSHOUT script - which means he'll be yellin' for help. If the doorman is killed before letting the party into the Estate, then that avenue is gone for the party permanently. Conversely, if the guard is bribed for 300 gold and then killed, the door is open and the bribe can be recovered from the dead guard's body. There is no reputation loss for this.\nMod content.\nPeople involved.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod makes some minor changes to the pirate's weapon proficiencies. Some SCS random treasure is also added to the creature's inventory."}
{"id": "26925", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=26925", "title": "Pirate Horn", "text": "The Pirate Horn is part of the quest &lt;a href=\"Leaving%20the%20island\"&gt;Leaving the island&lt;/a&gt; in \"Shadows of Amn\". It is needed to open the way out of the port on &lt;a href=\"Brynnlaw\"&gt;Brynnlaw&lt;/a&gt;. It is obtained by stealing it from &lt;a href=\"Cayia%27s%20House\"&gt;Cayia's House&lt;/a&gt; at night."}
{"id": "11985", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11985", "title": "Pit Fiend", "text": "Pit Fiends are baatezu devils encountered in-game or summoned by the &lt;a href=\"Gate\"&gt;Gate&lt;/a&gt; spell.\nPit Fiend versions.\nThe game has five different creature files for the Pit Fiend. The DEMPIT01.cre is encountered in &lt;a href=\"Spellhold%20Bodhi%27s%20Hunt%20Level%201\"&gt;Bodhi's Hunt Level 1&lt;/a&gt; underneath &lt;a href=\"Spellhold\"&gt;Spellhold&lt;/a&gt;. The DEMPITSU.cre is the version summoned from a &lt;a href=\"Gate\"&gt;Gate&lt;/a&gt; spell. The TELPIT1.cre is encountered on the &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Teleport%20Maze\"&gt;Teleport Maze &lt;/a&gt;.\nThe DEMPIT.cre and TELPIT2.cre are unused.\nGameplay.\nPit fiends conduct offensive actions on any enemy creatures in range with innate ability and melee attacks - typically at the closest target. Their attack script is repetitive and based on timed intervals between innate ability uses. The abilities can't really be interrupted by dealing damage to the fiend as the script uses a \"Force Cast\" command.\nParty members will be exposed to &lt;a href=\"Demon%20Fear\"&gt;Demon Fear&lt;/a&gt; initially, if close enough to the area of effect of the innate spell, which is directed at the nearest party member. Anyone in the area of effect will need to save vs. spell or potentially be under a two round &lt;a href=\"Panic\"&gt;Panic&lt;/a&gt; effect. This ability is used about every two rounds during combat.\nTwo varieties the fiend also will cast a &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt; at the party members closest to it (instantly). It will also explode an instantly launched &lt;a href=\"Fireball%20%28innate%29\"&gt;Fireball&lt;/a&gt; several times during a battle. Expect an instantly applied &lt;a href=\"Symbol%2C%20Fear%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Symbol, Fear&lt;/a&gt; spell as well. \nThe fiend will not recognize if a party member is protected against these magics, so it will rigidly just keep on physically attacking and launching spells, regardless of whether the party is protected. In that regard, the creature isn't adaptable or very intelligent.\nA pit fiend's general infernal immunities can vary slightly from one creature type to the next, but they all possess an &lt;a href=\"RINGDEMN.ITM\"&gt;undroppable item&lt;/a&gt; in their ring slot which provides the following protections:\nIn addition to this, a pit fiend can only be harmed by weapons of at least +3 enchantment.\nThe creature encountered inside Watcher's Keep (TELPIT1) is provided with more &lt;a href=\"XP\"&gt;XP&lt;/a&gt;, possesses 100 &lt;a href=\"HP\"&gt;HP&lt;/a&gt; and has 70% Magic resistance. It also uses a different script and employs &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Invisibility\"&gt;Improved Invisibility&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Flame%20Arrow\"&gt;Flame Arrow&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Hold%20Person\"&gt;Hold Person&lt;/a&gt; \"forcespell\" casts which can't be interrupted and have instant launch speeds. In addition, all of its &lt;a href=\"saving%20throw\"&gt;saving throw&lt;/a&gt;s have also been reduced, it is immune to &lt;a href=\"petrified\"&gt;petrification&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"backstab\"&gt;backstab&lt;/a&gt;, and it is &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;hasted&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe pit fiend in the game isn't fully developed to match what the Dungeons and Dragons 2nd edition ruleset establishes for this devil. Several special abilities, including the power to cast &lt;a href=\"Wish\"&gt;Wish&lt;/a&gt; and gate in other allies isn't implemented. It's supposed to have a constricting tail, and a disease inducing bite. The game version did get a few abilities right, such as the fear aura and some spell casting ability.\nLore bug.\nThe game identifies this creature as a Demon by race, and Tanar'ri by class, but it is actually a Devil and a Baatezu in Dungeons and Dragons lore. \nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod, and the \"Improved Fiends\" component will generally change the Pit Fiends in the game as follows:\nPit Fiends (cast at 24th level):&lt;br&gt;\nSmarter AI script&lt;br&gt;\nHP: 140 - 170 HP depending on variety&lt;br&gt;\nMovement Set to 11&lt;br&gt;\nAdditional elemental resistances&lt;br&gt;\nAdditional status effect and specific spell protections (level drain, fire-based spells)&lt;br&gt;\nTeleport without Error, Remove Magic, and Improved Invisibility, at will&lt;br&gt;\nMeteor Swarm and Unholy Word, once per day each&lt;br&gt;\nUnholy Fireball and Symbol of Fear, at will&lt;br&gt;\nPermanent fear aura&lt;br&gt;\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod (also works with SCS installed) will introduce new Pit Demons from the &lt;a href=\"Gate%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Gate (wizard)&lt;/a&gt; spell.&lt;br&gt;\nPit Fiend (20 Hit Dice, level 20/20/20 FMC class):\nSTR 24, DEX 16, CON 19, INT 20, WIS 16, CHA 25; AL Lawful Evil\nHP 170, AC -8, THAC0 -7, Saving Throws 4/6/4/8/6\n5 Attacks Per Round, 2d6+16 Piercing Damage (Claws, Bite, &amp; Tail +4)\nCombat Abilities (20% chance each):\nDisease: creatures struck by a pit fiend\u2019s bite attack must save vs. death at -4 or be infected with a vile disease known as devil chills, losing 2 points of strength after an incubation period of 12 hours\nPoison: a pit fiend\u2019s bite injects a lethal poison which inflicts 10 points of damage every second for 2 rounds unless a save vs. poison at -4 penalty is made\nConstrict: creatures struck by the pit fiend\u2019s tail must save vs. death at -4 to avoid being stunned for 1 round\nSpecial Qualities:\nImmune to weapons lower than +3 enchantment\nImmune to confusion, fear, poison, &amp; stun effects\nRegeneration: 2hp/round\nFire Resistance 100%; Cold Resistance 50%; Magic Resistance 65%\nSpecial Abilities:\nSee Invisibility (permanent)\nImproved Invisibility (at will)\nUnholy Fireball (once every 5 rounds)\nDispel Magic (once every 5 rounds)\nSymbol of Weakness (once every 5 rounds)\nUnholy Word (once per day)\nMeteor Swarm (once per day)"}
{"id": "41672", "revid": "235168", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=41672", "title": "Pit of the Faithless", "text": "The Pit of the Faithless is at the bottom of a hole accessed from the &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels%23Pit%20of%20the%20Faithless\"&gt;Cult Compound&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels\"&gt;The Old Tunnels&lt;/a&gt;, where people failing to survive the removal of their eyes are dumped.\nThe steady supply of corpses has led to an infestation of &lt;a href=\"Mummy\"&gt;mummies&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Zombie\"&gt;zombies&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Ghast\"&gt;ghasts&lt;/a&gt;, but also to a civilized society, complete with a mayor called &lt;a href=\"Theshal\"&gt;Theshal&lt;/a&gt;. These undead have given up on the living as a source of nutrition... that is, until they see and \"sssmellsss\" Gorion's Ward and Companions.\nAfter battling a few undead, you might spot a neutral talking Zombie who is surprised to see \"Living onesss?\" After he spots you, he shambles off to the northwest to inform the mayor.\"What isss thisss? What isss thisss? Living onesss? Here? I mussst tell the mayor!!\"\nAn exit to the east is labeled \"The Pit of the Faithless\" on the player's map and leads to the &lt;a href=\"Beholder%20Hideout\"&gt;Beholder Hideout&lt;/a&gt; where several &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;beholders&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Gauth\"&gt;gauths&lt;/a&gt;, a number of blind priests, and a mastermind beholder referred to as the &lt;a href=\"Unseeing%20Eye\"&gt;Unseeing Eye&lt;/a&gt; reside.\nBehind you, where you entered, the map is labeled \"To the Cult Compound\", however you cannot leave from here. Clicking on the area only gives you the status message: \"The pit above is too steep to climb back up. Numerous corpses lie below that have been picked clean.\"\nAhead of you there are bridges to landings and two ramshackle buildings to the northwest and northeast, both with doorways leading to &lt;a href=\"Ghoul%20Town\"&gt;Ghoul Town&lt;/a&gt;:"}
{"id": "50320", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50320", "title": "Pitch", "text": "Pitch is an Imp that looks like a Mephit, probably some kind of familiar that is with the &lt;a href=\"Adventuring%20Party%20%28Underdark%29\"&gt;Adventuring Party (Underdark)&lt;/a&gt;. \nGameplay.\nThis small, winged being can fire a &lt;a href=\"Mist%20Ball\"&gt;Mist Ball&lt;/a&gt; at a target, and again after a small delay interval. \nThe Mist Ball will blind a target for 10 seconds, with no saving throw. A save vs. Breath is needed to avoid 1d4+2 magic energy damage. Magic resistance can block it, as well as any Spell Protection. \nThe creature has a weak slashing attack as well. \nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod gives Pitch a few elemental immunities and some magic resistance, which it should have as an &lt;a href=\"Imp\"&gt;Imp&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "48704", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48704", "title": "Pitre", "text": "Pitre is one of four individuals found inside of a nondescript generic &lt;a href=\"Storehouse%20%28Bridge%20District%29\"&gt;building&lt;/a&gt; located in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge District&lt;/a&gt;. He's an evil human male cleric - and hostile from the get-go and will protect his comrades the second the party enters the premises.\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes a few changes to this creature. His weapon proficiencies are corrected to one pip in mace and 1 pip in Sword and shield style. If the \"Smarter Clerics\" component is installed, then Pitre will be able to instantly cast certain buffs that would be long-lasting in preparation of an encounter. The Cleric has a revised array of memorized spells. An SCS default script is assigned for smarter behavior in tactical situations. Finally, a few random SCS treasures are placed in his inventory. If a cloud-based spell is cast in the Storehouse, Pitre will attempt to get rid of it with a spell cast. \nIf the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; Mod is installed, the cleric's memorized spells will be the SR versions."}
{"id": "6080", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6080", "title": "Pixie Dust", "text": "Pixie Dust allows the caster to cloak his allies with invisibility. This invisibility is not of the type.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this Divine spell, revising its effects, duration, school, and description. See below:\nPixie Dust\nLevel: 5\nSchool: Conjuration\nSphere: Combat\nRange: Personal\nDuration: 1 turn\nCasting Time: 5\nArea of Effect: 30\u2019 radius\nSaving Throw: None\nThis spell creates a handful of pixie dust that the caster can toss into the air. Allies covered by the dust becomes improved invisible for 1 turn."}
{"id": "6969", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6969", "title": "Pixie Prick", "text": "Pixie Prick is an &lt;a href=\"Enchanted%20item\"&gt;enchanted&lt;/a&gt; dagger +3 which can make enemies fall asleep for two rounds when they fail their save roll vs. poison (with a bonus of 6 to the &lt;a href=\"saving%20throw\"&gt;saving throw&lt;/a&gt; in the original \"Shadows of Amn\"). In the Enhanced Editions the dagger is now op-coded to provide elves with a 90% chance to resist the sleep effect, and half elves with a 30% resistance. The sleep effect can be dispelled and is unaffected by magic resistance. The unconsciousness won't be removed by getting hurt while asleep, such as by a subsequent hit during the sleep duration."}
{"id": "13026", "revid": "24784390", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13026", "title": "Pixie Prick +3", "text": ""}
{"id": "56078", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=56078", "title": "Plague (card)", "text": "The Plague card, can be drawn from the deck of many things when agreeing to play a game with &lt;a href=\"Aesgareth\"&gt;Aesgareth&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Teleport%20Maze\"&gt;Watcher's Keep Teleport Maze&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis page is to document the potential spell effects of this card when it is drawn.\nGameplay.\nWhen a party member character engages in the first card draw contest with Aesgareth, there is an even chance of drawing the Plague card, or the &lt;a href=\"Strife%20%28card%29\"&gt;Strife (card)&lt;/a&gt;.\nIf this card is drawn, the script controlled by Aesgareth's dialogue will apply this spell to the party member who drew the card.\nThe spell will animate a graphic visual effect and color glow over the character, and the combat log will display a text reading \"Plague\".\nA \"Cursed\" icon is placed in the character's portrait.\nThe target is now affected by a &lt;a href=\"Constitution\"&gt;Constitution&lt;/a&gt; modifier effect which sets the target's CON to a value of 6. This effect will not expire.\nThis spell has no school, nor any assigned secondary type. It is unaffected by magic resistance, and all of its internal components have a 0 &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis essentially means that there is no method available to the player to block this spell.\nAs the effect is coded to be a curse, a &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Curse\"&gt;Remove Curse&lt;/a&gt; is needed to eliminate it. \nA &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effect won't work on this spell."}
{"id": "28140", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=28140", "title": "Planar Key", "text": "This Planar Key can be found in the &lt;a href=\"Inside%20the%20Planar%20Sphere%23The%20Guardian%27s%20Room\"&gt;Guardian's Room&lt;/a&gt; which is located to the left after you have entered the &lt;a href=\"Inside%20the%20Planar%20Sphere\"&gt;Planar Sphere&lt;/a&gt;. It allows for further exploration of the sphere by unlocking the door that leads to the &lt;a href=\"Inside%20the%20Planar%20Sphere%23The%20Welcome%20Room\"&gt;Welcome Room&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "13207", "revid": "274969", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13207", "title": "Planar Prison", "text": "The Planar Prison can be accessed only during the quest to &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20planar%20prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the planar prison&lt;/a&gt;, the party may not return to it after the quest.\nWalkthrough.\nLanding Zone.\nPlanar Bounty Hunters.\nEntering the Portal from the &lt;a href=\"Five%20Flagons%20Theatre\"&gt;Playhouse&lt;/a&gt; in the basement of the &lt;a href=\"Five%20Flagons%20Inn\"&gt;Five Flagons Inn&lt;/a&gt;, lands you in a circular area where you interrupt the interrogation of a prisoner by the same Extra-Planar Bounty Hunters who abducted &lt;a href=\"Raelis%20Shai\"&gt;Raelis Shai&lt;/a&gt; and her Sigil Theatre Troupe.\nThrough dialog their leader is revealed: &lt;a href=\"Aawill\"&gt;Aawill&lt;/a&gt;. He is using his &lt;a href=\"Yuan-ti\"&gt;Yuan-Ti&lt;/a&gt; henchman named &lt;a href=\"T%27rael\"&gt;T'rael&lt;/a&gt; to force the gnome prisoner &lt;a href=\"Tagget\"&gt;Tagget&lt;/a&gt; to divulge how he removed his &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20Collar\"&gt;Thrall Collar&lt;/a&gt;, \"...or you'll find there are far worse things than being a slave!\" One of the &lt;a href=\"Bounty%20Hunter%20%28Planar%20Prison%20Fighter%29\"&gt;Bounty Hunter elf fighters&lt;/a&gt; warns the yuan-ti of the party's arrival: \"T'rael! Hold! Others have come through the portal!\" Aawill then turns his attention towards you, revealing a third name, &lt;a href=\"Von%27ith\"&gt;Von'ith&lt;/a&gt;, as he instructs her to deny escape:\"What? Others? Ah...the primes. How foolish of you to have followed your actor friends here. Von'ith, close the portal, please. Heh. Do you have any idea at all where you are, primes?\"\nYou then have a brief chance for dialog before the hunters attack. After the battle, be sure to gather their possessions. Besides Aawill, T'rael and Von'ith, the two &lt;a href=\"Bounty%20Hunter%20%28Planar%20Prison%20Fighter%29\"&gt;elf fighters&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Bounty%20Hunter%20%28Planar%20Prison%20Thief%29\"&gt;halfling thief&lt;/a&gt; round out the group. The entire group is worth .\nThe center of the landing zone is dominated by a fleshy, toothy cavern, forcing one to walk around it to the north and east. Clicking on it reveals: \"This cavern leads downward and seems to pulse slightly, almost as if it were breathing.\" Repeated clicks give the same message.\nWhile you're looting the dead bounty hunters, Tagget will eventually get up the nerve to talk you automatically.\nTagget.\nApproach &lt;a href=\"Tagget\"&gt;Tagget&lt;/a&gt;, a gnome who recently released himself from his &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20Collar\"&gt;Thrall Collar&lt;/a&gt;, and he will tell you what to expect. Given a chance, Tagget has quite a lot to say about:\nAfter destroying the Mastery Orb, Tagget will talk to you again to express his gratitude, granting the party another .\nFleshy Traps in Area File Order.\nFleshy Traps suck you down into a separate pit to be ambushed by more enemies. It can be very difficult to get from one side of the path to the other without being caught. Furthermore, they separate party members since they only pull down those too close to the center, possibly resulting in a divided party fighting on multiple fronts simultaneously. A status message appears as you encounter them.\"The strange fleshy trap has sucked a party member down into another chamber below.\"\nSilent Spawn Triggers.\nThere are two silent triggers that spawn different groups of monsters depending upon current &lt;a href=\"Experience%20Tables\"&gt;experience points&lt;/a&gt; accrued by &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt;.\nOne trigger is in the middle of the path to the east of the Landing Zone before reaching the Thrall Leader. These monsters spawn further to the east where the Female Thrall is guarding the &lt;a href=\"Wyvern%20%28Warden%27s%20Pet%29\"&gt;Warden's Pet Wyvern&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe other trigger is west of the Master of Thralls, just before the two fleshy traps east of the Prison Warden. These monsters spawn further to the west where the Prison Warden is, adding an extra level of difficulty to the final battle.\nThralls.\nBrazier Chamber.\nEast of the portal landing is a group of three Thralls who try to warn you \"Go, strangers! We cannot control our actions... we... we... attack them!\" If &lt;a href=\"Jaheira\"&gt;Jaheira&lt;/a&gt; is in the party, she will lament, \"These people are slaves, mentally as well as physically, controlled despite themselves. All we can offer them, unfortunately, is a quick death.\" Other &lt;a href=\"companions\"&gt;companions&lt;/a&gt; may also interject comments. The group has a &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20Leader\"&gt;Thrall Leader&lt;/a&gt; (), a female &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20%28Mage%29\"&gt;Thrall Mage&lt;/a&gt; (), and a &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20Fighter\"&gt;Thrall Fighter&lt;/a&gt; (). A treasure stash in the northwest corner has a scroll of &lt;a href=\"Armor\"&gt;Armor&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Arrow%20of%20Biting\"&gt;Arrows of Biting&lt;/a&gt; , and mundane missiles: Arrows , Bolts , Bullets , Darts .\nThe Brazier.\nIn the center is a brazier. At the moment, clicking it only gives the message, \"The brazier glows with a searing heat. An arm reaches from the fire as if waiting to grasp something and draw it into the heat.\" Repeated clicks give the same message. \nAfter taking the &lt;a href=\"Mastery%20Orb\"&gt;Mastery Orb&lt;/a&gt; from the Master of Thralls, you can return to the Brazier Room and click on the brazier to destroy the orb, thereby releasing the Thralls. Doing so grants the party and displays a status message:\"You place the orb in the outstretched arm and watch as the orb is drawn into the searing heat. For a moment, nothing happens. You hear a cracking noise and the orb bursts.\"All the thralls in the map will turn friendly and start attacking enemies near them, including the Warden. This will make the fight against the Warden much easier if you hurry towards him as he will expend his spells on the thralls. Once the Warden is defeated, they will immediately teleport out of the map, making whatever loot you would have gotten from killing them unobtainable!\nTo the east of the brazier chamber is a fleshy trap (as noted above) with &lt;a href=\"Githyanki\"&gt;Githyanki&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Warden's Pet.\nIn the southeastern area is a female &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20%28Elf%20Mage%29\"&gt;Elf Thrall Mage&lt;/a&gt; who, along with another &lt;a href=\"Female%20Thrall\"&gt;Female Thrall&lt;/a&gt;\", \"must protect the Warden's pet!\" ( each thrall). In addition, a silent trigger will have spawned several other enemy monsters here (see \"&lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison%23Silent%20Spawn%20Triggers\"&gt;Silent Spawn Triggers&lt;/a&gt;\"\" above). Furthermore, during battle the &lt;a href=\"Wyvern%20%28Warden%27s%20Pet%29\"&gt;\"Warden's pet\" Wyvern&lt;/a&gt; () might also join the fray from the area just north of them. After the battle, loot the Female Thrall for &lt;a href=\"Kundane\"&gt;Kundane&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Xarrnous%27s%20Second%20Sword%20Arm\"&gt;Xarrnous's Second Sword Arm&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20the%20Princes\"&gt;Ring of the Princes&lt;/a&gt;. Loot the Elf Thrall Mage for &lt;a href=\"Bracers%20of%20Defense%20AC%208\"&gt;Bracers of Defense AC 8&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Lightning\"&gt;Wand of Lightning&lt;/a&gt;, and a &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Extra%20Healing\"&gt;Potion of Extra Healing&lt;/a&gt;. Turn north to see the Wyvern's Perch (on which, clicking gives a status message):\"The wyvern's perch twitches as if it lives and is soft and organic to the touch.\"\nMaster of Thralls.\nWest of the wyvern perch is the &lt;a href=\"Master%20of%20Thralls\"&gt;Master of Thralls&lt;/a&gt; (), a demon who shouts an angry threat before willing into being a pair of &lt;a href=\"Air%20Elemental\"&gt;Air Elementals&lt;/a&gt; ( each).\nAfterwards when the Master is dead, a &lt;a href=\"Dwarf%20Thrall\"&gt;Dwarf Thrall&lt;/a&gt; will be amazed that, \"You...you have killed the master! You have killed him! By Clangeddin's Axe, I thought such a thing not even possible!\" You may then ask him questions, and if you are fast enough (now equipped with the Boots of Speed), pickpocket him for some gold before he disappears, saying \"I...I must flee before the Warden discovers the Master of Thralls is dead! Please...destroy the orb if you are able! I beg of you!!\"\nLoot the Master of Thralls for his &lt;a href=\"Staff%20of%20Air\"&gt;Staff of Air +2&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Mastery%20Orb\"&gt;Mastery Orb&lt;/a&gt;. In the northeast corner is a treasure stash with &lt;a href=\"Dart%20of%20Stunning\"&gt;Darts of Stunning&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Waterstar%20Gem\"&gt;Waterstar Gem&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn the center of the area, is another pit. Clicking (and re-clicking) gives you another message:\"Mists swirl deep within this hole, perhaps a portal to elsewhere.\"\nTo the west of the Master of Thralls are two fleshy traps (as noted above), with Wolfweres and Efreeti.\nThe Planar Prison Warden.\nNorth of the Landing Zone is the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Warden&lt;/a&gt; of this \"pocket plane\" prison, but before he can be reached, you must pass two \"fleshy traps\" to the south and east of him. The traps to the east have room on either side to pass by, while those to the south can not be skirted. For the latter, upon exiting, you find yourself on the north side of each of the traps, closer and closer to a dangerous ambush set up by the Warden and his thralls. As Tagget said, it's much better to go east than north.\nBesides being a powerful cambion, the Warden is an 18th Level &lt;a href=\"Specialist%20Mage\"&gt;Conjurer&lt;/a&gt;, able to cast deadly spells such as &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Kill\"&gt;Power Word: Kill&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Finger%20of%20Death%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Finger of Death&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Disintegrate\"&gt;Disintegrate&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Abi-Dalzim%27s%20Horrid%20Wilting\"&gt;Abi-Dalzim's Horrid Wilting&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Flesh%20to%20Stone\"&gt;Flesh to Stone&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Imprisonment\"&gt;Imprisonment&lt;/a&gt;, all while using &lt;a href=\"True%20Sight\"&gt;True Sight&lt;/a&gt; to spy out your stealthy characters.\nTwo male &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20%28Mage%29\"&gt;Thrall Mages&lt;/a&gt; ( each) and a female &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20%28Cleric%29\"&gt;Thrall Cleric&lt;/a&gt; () also await you, along with &lt;a href=\"Warden%20Thrall\"&gt;Warden Thrall&lt;/a&gt;s ( ). In addition, a silent trigger will have spawned several other enemy monsters here (see \"\"&lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison%23Silent%20Spawn%20Triggers\"&gt;Silent Spawn Triggers&lt;/a&gt;\"\" above). The two mages begin battle with Protection from &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Normal%20Weapons\"&gt;Normal Weapons&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Electricity%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Electricity&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Door\"&gt;Shadow Door&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Contingency\"&gt;Contingency&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;, then attack with &lt;a href=\"Chain%20Lightning\"&gt;Chain Lightning&lt;/a&gt;. A tough battle if you face them all at once, just after having stepped out of a fleshy trap.\nAfter the battle, loot the Warden for his &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison%20Cell%20Key\"&gt;Planar Prison Cell Key&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Adjatha%20the%20Drinker\"&gt;Adjatha the Drinker&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Wave%20Shaft\"&gt;Wave Shaft&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Star%20Sapphire\"&gt;Star Sapphire&lt;/a&gt; , &lt;a href=\"Emerald\"&gt;Emerald&lt;/a&gt; , and . Also loot his Thralls for minor magical items (&lt;a href=\"Long%20Sword%20%2B1\"&gt;Long Swords +1&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"War%20Hammer%20%2B1\"&gt;War Hammer +1&lt;/a&gt;, etc). A treasure stash to the southwest has &lt;a href=\"Bolt%20of%20Biting\"&gt;Bolts of Biting&lt;/a&gt; , &lt;a href=\"Bullet%20%2B1\"&gt;Bullets +1&lt;/a&gt; , Throwing Axes , and Throwing Daggers .\nThe center of the Warden's chamber has a \"throne chair\" [that] \"looks to be more of a device of torture than anything else.\"\nThe Warden's Cell.\nBeyond the Warden's throne room to the west is the cell holding Raelis, Haer'Dalis, and the rest of the Sigil Theatre Troupe. If there is anything else you wish to do before leaving the Planar Prison, do so BEFORE entering the cell, as you will not get another chance, and you can never return here again.\nUpon entering the Warden's prison cell, a cut-scene begins with Haer'Dalis greeting the party, followed by Raelis. The two then have a discussion, the results of which are Haer'Dalis wants to leave the Troupe and explore the Prime Material plane.\nIf eligible, Raelis offers you the Deed to the &lt;a href=\"Five%20Flagons%20Theatre\"&gt;Playhouse&lt;/a&gt;, which you can accept or not.\nAfter all of this, Raelis summons another \"young conduit\" and you are transported back to the Playhouse, where Haer'Dalis will offer to join your party. Accept gladly, Deny harshly, or say, perhaps another time.\nIf you accepted the Deed to the Playhouse, another cut-scene occurs with &lt;a href=\"Samuel%20Thunderburp\"&gt;Samuel Thunderburp&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Higgold\"&gt;Higgold&lt;/a&gt; the Director, thus beginning the &lt;a href=\"Bard\"&gt;Bard&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Stronghold\"&gt;Stronghold&lt;/a&gt; Quest, &lt;a href=\"Running%20the%20Five%20Flagons%20Playhouse\"&gt;Running the Five Flagons Playhouse&lt;/a&gt;.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes revisions to all creatures found in the prison, including spawns. Of particular note are the differences from the unmodified game to the SCS gameplay if the \"Better Calls for Help\" component is installed. In the unmodified game, the party can methodically traverse the map, and encounter enemies in groups, essentially one by one. With the SCS component, once the party sets out and alerts the prison defenders, creatures from other locations on the map will often enter the fray at random times in an unexpected manner, sometimes with three or more extra defenders being present. This can be used to your advantage or may be a burden, throwing off the usual tactics planned. \nWith SCS version 34, the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Prison Warden&lt;/a&gt; has been slightly toned down from the previous SCS version (possibly from player feedback). The warden will no longer cast and be armed with the &lt;a href=\"Black%20Blade%20of%20Disaster\"&gt;Black Blade of Disaster&lt;/a&gt; or cast &lt;a href=\"Time%20Stop\"&gt;Time Stop&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Imprisonment\"&gt;Imprisonment&lt;/a&gt; as was reported. As the party experience level may be middling at this part of the saga, that may have been too difficult to overcome. The latest version of SCS still has the warden configured to provide a good challenge for a \"boss\".\nThe &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Construction%20for%20Spellcasters\"&gt;Golem Construction for Spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; mod places two additional Lesser Golems in one of the \"Fleshy Trap\" prison cells."}
{"id": "51142", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51142", "title": "Planar Prison Cell 1 (closest to wyvern)", "text": "The Planar Prison Cell 1 (closest to Wyvern) is a chamber that is accessed only by getting sucked down by a \"Fleshy Trap\" and is part of the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; complex - reachable only during the quest to &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20planar%20prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the planar prison&lt;/a&gt;. \nA single member or group of party companions can be drawn in, if near the edge or on top of the pulsating trap. When a member is drawn into the object, the player message screen displays \"The strange fleshy trap has sucked a party member down into another chamber below.\"\nAnyone drawn down into the chamber will immediately be faced with a hostile group. If quick enough, party members can attempt to reverse their path and exit the fleshy trap chamber by standing upon the pulsating orifice, which if done correctly will move the party member back up to the Planar Prison, where they were initially \"sucked below\". If they remain in the chamber, they must face attacks by the inhabitants of the prison cell. \nOnce the cell inhabitants are defeated, no other spawns or enemies will be present within. \nInhabitants.\nThere are five &lt;a href=\"Githyanki\"&gt;Githyanki&lt;/a&gt; creatures within, all of which are armed, and most are wearing plate armor. They are hostile and will attempt to kill any party members drawn inside their current area of control. \nThe &lt;a href=\"Gish%20%28githyanki%29\"&gt;Gish&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Knight%20%28githyanki%29\"&gt;Knight&lt;/a&gt; and three &lt;a href=\"Warrior%20%28githyanki%29\"&gt;Warrior&lt;/a&gt; creatures collectively attack with innate Psionic abilities, melee attacks and spell casting actions. Most likely, expect them to initially quaff potions of invisibility in order to gain an advantage.\nThere is a container in the chamber that can be searched. Contents include mundane missiles: Throwing Daggers , Arrows , Bolts , Bullets , and Darts .\nMod content.\nWith the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod installed, all the Githyanki are standardized, and revised. New default scripts are assigned for smarter tactical behavior, additional psionic abilities, and the \"Smarter Mage\" component for the Gish. Potions will still be used as in the unmodified game. There are no level 3 Githyanki with SCS, so those warriors will be level 9 fighters now. For more details see the individual creature pages linked above."}
{"id": "51169", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51169", "title": "Planar Prison Cell 2 (east of warden)", "text": "The Planar Prison Cell 2 (east of the warden) is a chamber that is accessed only by getting sucked down by a \"Fleshy Trap\" and is part of the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; complex - reachable only during the quest to &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20planar%20prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the planar prison&lt;/a&gt;. The location of the trap is east of the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Prison Warden&lt;/a&gt;, and west of the &lt;a href=\"Master%20of%20Thralls\"&gt;Master of Thralls&lt;/a&gt; for further clarification.\nA single member or group of party companions can be drawn in, if near the edge or on top of the pulsating trap. When a member is drawn into the object, the player message screen displays \"The strange fleshy trap has sucked a party member down into another chamber below.\"\nAnyone drawn down into the chamber will immediately be faced with a hostile group. If quick enough, party members can attempt to reverse their path and exit the fleshy trap chamber by standing upon the pulsating orifice, which if done correctly will move the party member back up to the Planar Prison, where they were initially \"sucked below\". If they remain in the chamber, they must face attacks by the inhabitants of the prison cell. \nInhabitants.\nThere are five creatures within, and they look similar, one is a &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Wolfwere\"&gt;Greater Wolfwere&lt;/a&gt; and the other four are &lt;a href=\"Wolfwere\"&gt;Wolfwere's&lt;/a&gt;. These fierce beasts will immediately lunge at the party with crazed bloodlust and frenzied claw and biting attacks. The party must defend itself, before being shredded and torn asunder. \nIf defeated, the chamber yields no found valuables in the grisly mess. This chamber will now be free of further inhabitants or spawned enemies. The party may exit the map via the Exit Icon (shown with the map cursor)."}
{"id": "51170", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51170", "title": "Planar Prison Cell 3 (next to cell 2)", "text": "The Planar Prison Cell 3 (next to cell 2) is a chamber that is accessed only by getting sucked down by a \"Fleshy Trap\" and is part of the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; complex - reachable only during the quest to &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20planar%20prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the planar prison&lt;/a&gt;. The location of the trap is east of the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Prison Warden&lt;/a&gt;, and next to &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison%20Cell%202%20%28east%20of%20warden%29\"&gt;Planar Prison Cell 2 (east of warden)&lt;/a&gt; and west of the &lt;a href=\"Master%20of%20Thralls\"&gt;Master of Thralls&lt;/a&gt; for further clarification.\nA single member or group of party companions can be drawn in, if near the edge or on top of the pulsating trap. When a member is drawn into the object, the player message screen displays \"The strange fleshy trap has sucked a party member down into another chamber below.\"\nAnyone drawn down into the chamber will immediately be faced with a hostile group. If quick enough, party members can attempt to reverse their path and exit the fleshy trap chamber by standing upon the pulsating orifice, which if done correctly will move the party member back up to the Planar Prison, where they were initially \"sucked below\". If they remain in the chamber, they must face attacks by the inhabitants of the prison cell. \nInhabitants.\nThere are three creatures within, and they have a similar look, one is a &lt;a href=\"Efreeti%20%28Noble%29\"&gt;Efreeti (Noble)&lt;/a&gt; and the other two are &lt;a href=\"Efreeti\"&gt;Efreeti&lt;/a&gt;. These magical genies from the elemental plane of fire will immediately respond to any intrusion with attacks upon the party. The creatures have various fire-based spell attacks, as well as slashing and bruising melee strikes. It is possible that one or more may become invisible to gain an advantage later in the confrontation. \nIf defeated, the chamber yields no found valuables after the strange encounter. Just the acrid odor of brimstone and the charred scorch marks left on the cell surfaces. This chamber will now be free of further inhabitants or spawned enemies. The party may exit the map via the Exit Icon (shown with the map cursor)."}
{"id": "51171", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51171", "title": "Planar Prison Cell 4 (south of warden)", "text": "The Planar Prison Cell 4 (south of warden) is a chamber that is accessed only by getting sucked down by a \"Fleshy Trap\" and is part of the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; complex - reachable only during the quest to &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20planar%20prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the planar prison&lt;/a&gt;. The location of the trap is south of the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Prison Warden&lt;/a&gt;, and north of the landing zone where the party entered the Planar Prison complex. It is also adjacent to &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison%20Cell%205%20%28next%20to%20cell%204%29\"&gt;Planar Prison Cell 5&lt;/a&gt; for further clarification.\nA single member or group of party companions can be drawn in, if near the edge or on top of the pulsating trap. When a member is drawn into the object, the player message screen displays \"The strange fleshy trap has sucked a party member down into another chamber below.\"\nAnyone drawn down into the chamber will immediately be faced with a hostile group. If quick enough, party members can attempt to reverse their path and exit the fleshy trap chamber by standing upon the pulsating orifice, which if done correctly will move the party member back up to the Planar Prison, where they were initially \"sucked below\". If they remain in the chamber, they must face attacks by the inhabitants of the prison cell. \nInhabitants.\nThere are several creatures within, and these include Four &lt;a href=\"Minotaur\"&gt;Minotaur&lt;/a&gt;, an elven &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Captain%20%28Fighter%29\"&gt;Prison Captain (Fighter)&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Captain%20%28Fighter%20Mage%29\"&gt;Prison Captain (Fighter Mage)&lt;/a&gt;. Upon any party member entering the cell, hostilities will commence. The F/M will attempt a self-buff, the Fighter will engage in combat, while the minotaur group will rush toward the party to slash them with their battle axe weaponry. \nIf defeated, the chamber yields several items of equipment carried by the fallen combatants. See the applicable creature pages linked above for details. This chamber will now be free of further inhabitants or spawned enemies. The party may exit the map via the Exit Icon (shown with the map cursor)."}
{"id": "51172", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51172", "title": "Planar Prison Cell 5 (next to cell 4)", "text": "The Planar Prison Cell 5 (next to cell 4) is a chamber that is accessed only by getting sucked down by a \"Fleshy Trap\" and is part of the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; complex - reachable only during the quest to &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20planar%20prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the planar prison&lt;/a&gt;. The location of the trap is south of the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Prison Warden&lt;/a&gt;, and north of the landing zone where the party entered the Planar Prison complex. It is also adjacent to &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison%20Cell%204%20%28south%20of%20warden%29\"&gt;Planar Prison Cell 4&lt;/a&gt; for further clarification.\nA single member or group of party companions can be drawn in, if near the edge or on top of the pulsating trap. When a member is drawn into the object, the player message screen displays \"The strange fleshy trap has sucked a party member down into another chamber below.\"\nAnyone drawn down into the chamber will immediately be faced with a hostile group. If quick enough, party members can attempt to reverse their path and exit the fleshy trap chamber by standing upon the pulsating orifice, which if done correctly will move the party member back up to the Planar Prison, where they were initially \"sucked below\". If they remain in the chamber, they must face attacks by the inhabitants of the prison cell. \nInhabitants.\nThere are several creatures within, including three elven adversaries - a &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Captain%20%28Cleric%29\"&gt;Prison Captain (Cleric)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Captain%20%28Mage%29\"&gt;Prison Captain (Mage)&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Captain%20%28Fighter%20Mage%29\"&gt;Prison Captain (Fighter Mage)&lt;/a&gt;. Further, there is a &lt;a href=\"Clay%20Golem\"&gt;Clay Golem&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Stone%20Golem\"&gt;Stone Golem&lt;/a&gt; present. Upon any party member entering the cell, hostilities will commence. The Mage will launch a contingency self-buff. The F/M and Cleric will attempt a self-buff cast. The two golems will charge forward, and the Clay Golem may release its innate &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Haste\"&gt;Golem Haste&lt;/a&gt; ability. The Stone golem may also discharge its innate &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Slow\"&gt;Golem Slow&lt;/a&gt; power as well. The golems will then seek to pound the party with crushing blows. The Mage will continue to cast spells, unless disrupted. Both the cleric and F/M may try to get additional spells cast, but if disrupted could be forced to fight in close quarters combat.\nIf defeated, the chamber yields several items of equipment and other loot carried by the fallen elven combatants. See the applicable creature pages linked above for details. This chamber will now be free of further inhabitants or spawned enemies. The party may exit the map via the Exit Icon (shown with the map cursor). Exiting this chamber will put the party member right next to the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Prison Warden&lt;/a&gt; throne area. This will imitate further attacks on the party.\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Construction%20for%20Spellcasters\"&gt;Golem Construction for Spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; Mod adds two extra opponent creatures to this area, a Lesser Clay Golem and Lesser Stone Golem. These positions are shown on the Map in the InfoBox."}
{"id": "38906", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=38906", "title": "Planar Prison Cell Key", "text": "The Planar Prison Cell Key is dropped by the &lt;a href=\"Prison%20Warden\"&gt;Prison Warden&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; during the quest &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt;. It can be used to open the prison doors and rescue &lt;a href=\"Raelis%20Shai\"&gt;Raelis Shai&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Haer%27Dalis\"&gt;Haer'Dalis&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "7607", "revid": "40332393", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7607", "title": "Planar Sphere", "text": ""}
{"id": "51429", "revid": "35642161", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51429", "title": "Planar Sphere Mod", "text": "The Planar Sphere Mod fills the previously rather empty BG2 &lt;a href=\"Mage%20Stronghold\"&gt;mage stronghold&lt;/a&gt; with characters, encounters, and mini-quests, and also adds an intense, combat-heavy quest-line about saving the multiverse from an evil archsorcerer.\nStatus.\nIt is a very old mod that has been updated by different modders between 2002 and 2008, and was then abandoned.\nThe latest version (\"codice_1\" from 2008) is not natively compatible with the of the game, but can be made so by applying the &lt;a href=\"https%3A//github.com/BigWorldSetup/BigWorldSetup-Fixpack/tree/master/Big%2520World%2520Fixpack\"&gt;Big World Fixpack&lt;/a&gt; patches. Even then, it does not become &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition%20Trilogy\"&gt;EET&lt;/a&gt; compatible.\nHowever, the \"&lt;a href=\"Expanded%20Mage%20Stronghold\"&gt;Expanded Mage Stronghold&lt;/a&gt;\" mod (which is a nerfed version of this mod without the big archsorcerer quest-line) is fully &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition%20Trilogy\"&gt;EET&lt;/a&gt;-compatible.\nOverview.\nMage stronghold brought to life.\nA few days after the party completes the normal &lt;a href=\"Mage%20Stronghold\"&gt;mage stronghold&lt;/a&gt; quest-line, &lt;a href=\"Teos\"&gt;Teos&lt;/a&gt; appears in the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Sphere\"&gt;Planar Sphere&lt;/a&gt; again and proposes a new arrangement.\nThe Planar Sphere is turned into a sprawling &lt;a href=\"Cowled%20Wizard\"&gt;Cowled Wizard&lt;/a&gt; academy, which adds content to almost every room of the sphere:\nEvil archsorcerer quest-line.\nThis large quest-line starts after the Planar Sphere has been turned into a Cowled Wizard academy.\nAn uber-powerful archsorcerer is trying to implode the planes of existence, and the gods and overgods are powerless to stop him. The fate of the entire multiverse now hinges on the player-controlled party...\nThe combat encounters in this quest are so tough, that some players consider it a tactical-challenge mod in the vein of \"&lt;a href=\"Tactics%20Mod\"&gt;Weimer's Tactics Mod&lt;/a&gt;\".\nExternal links.\n\"(For the mod's main website/forum/download page, see the infobox above.)\""}
{"id": "37697", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37697", "title": "Planehopper", "text": ""}
{"id": "8942", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8942", "title": "Planetar", "text": "A Planetar is a powerful Celestial being summoned using the &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Planetar\"&gt;Summon Planetar&lt;/a&gt;. It is the good counterpart to the &lt;a href=\"Dark%20Planetar\"&gt;Dark Planetar&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Planetar uses the Solar animation and has a bluish tint.\nGameplay.\nCombat.\nWith 110 hit points, 10% physical damage resistance, immunity to cold/fire/electricity, 75% &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic Resistance&lt;/a&gt;, 3 &lt;a href=\"Globe%20of%20Blades\"&gt;Globe of Blades&lt;/a&gt; and 3 &lt;a href=\"Heal\"&gt;Heal&lt;/a&gt; spells memorized as well as numerous effect immunities, Planetars are quite resilient, capable of holding their ground against both hard-hitting melee enemies and high-level spellcasters.\nPlanetars can &lt;a href=\"See%20the%20invisible\"&gt;See the invisible&lt;/a&gt; as an innate power.\nPlanetars are under a permanent &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;normal haste&lt;/a&gt; effect and, in &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition\"&gt;Enhanced Edition&lt;/a&gt;s only, have an extremely fast &lt;a href=\"regeneration\"&gt;regeneration&lt;/a&gt; rate of 8 HP per second (4HP/sec doubled by the haste effect). A Planetar is considered \"gated\" rather than \"summoned\", and thus cannot be banished by a &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt;. \nThe summoned Planetar wields a +3 &lt;a href=\"Magical%20item\"&gt;magical Greatsword&lt;/a&gt; that deals 2D10+3 &lt;a href=\"Slashing%20damage\"&gt;Slashing damage&lt;/a&gt;, with an extra +7 for the Planetar's Strength. The Sword is the item that gives the Planetar its Normal &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;Haste effect&lt;/a&gt;, raising its &lt;a href=\"Attacks%20per%20round\"&gt;APR&lt;/a&gt; to 4.\nThe Planetar uses a script for melee combat that evaluates enemy use of &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; and if the Planetar's weapon is ineffective (from some kind of spell or immunity). The Planetar's AI will look for alternate targets moving to the second, then third closest enemy it can detect.\nEach blow from this weapon has a 25% chance to:\nThese effects bypass &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;.\nSpellcasting.\nThe Planetar's primary class is Mage (level 25), but it also has a hidden default Cleric spell casting ability, meaning all Cleric spells will be cast at level 1, not level 25. This makes &lt;a href=\"Flame%20Strike\"&gt;Flame Strike&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Symbol%2C%20Fear%20%28priest%29\"&gt;Symbol, Fear&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Holy%20Word\"&gt;Holy Word&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic%20%28priest%29\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; have their minimum possible effectiveness (which varies, as spells tend to scale starting from the level they're normally obtainable and others, like Holy Word, don't scale at all). This has been tested and confirmed for BG2EE.\nWithout player command, a Planetar's &lt;a href=\"Game%20Terminology%23A\"&gt;AI&lt;/a&gt; will only cast &lt;a href=\"Lesser%20Restoration\"&gt;Lesser Restoration&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Neutralize%20Poison\"&gt;Neutralize Poison&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Fear\"&gt;Remove Fear&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Cure%20Disease\"&gt;Cure Disease&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Heal\"&gt;Heal&lt;/a&gt; (including its scripted self-Heal ability) and &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic%20%28priest%29\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; as needed; all other spells require the player to manually cast them from the Planetar's spellbook.\nIt will cast \"Heal\" if a party member is within detection range and hit points have fallen below 25% of maximum. The other curative spells are cast if the planetar detects &lt;a href=\"Level%20drain\"&gt;Level drain&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;State: Poisoned&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Panic\"&gt;State: Panic&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Disease\"&gt;State: Diseased&lt;/a&gt;. If a player character is detected and under a &lt;a href=\"Charmed\"&gt;State: Charmed&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Confused\"&gt;State: Confused&lt;/a&gt; it will attempt its caster level 1 Dispel Magic (don't count on that being successful).\nNotes.\nPlanetars aren't encountered as enemies during normal gameplay. If, however, a player-summoned Planetar becomes hostile for some reason, &lt;a href=\"Death%20Ward\"&gt;Death Ward&lt;/a&gt; is one way to defend against the &lt;a href=\"Kill%20target\"&gt;Vorpal hit effect&lt;/a&gt;. Spells that protect from +3 weapons (e.g. &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Mantle\"&gt;Improved Mantle&lt;/a&gt;) also prevent the effect from triggering. Alternatively, increasing the defender's &lt;a href=\"saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving Throw&lt;/a&gt; vs. Death (e.g. &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Invisibility\"&gt;Improved Invisibility&lt;/a&gt;) to -1 or below will prevent the vorpal effect from killing the defender.\nThe physical and magical resilience of the Planetar, combined with its vorpal attacks, makes it useful for pretty much any combat encounter. As an example, if given the appropriate pre-buffs, it is entirely feasible for a Planetar to defeat high-level enemies such as &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;beholders&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Lich\"&gt;liches&lt;/a&gt;, or even a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Dragon\"&gt;shadow dragon&lt;/a&gt; single-handedly.\n&lt;a href=\"Shadows%20of%20Amn\"&gt;Shadows of Amn&lt;/a&gt; was initially designed without &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;high-level class abilities&lt;/a&gt; like Summon Planetar; player characters were limited to 2.95 million &lt;a href=\"Experience%20Tables\"&gt;XP&lt;/a&gt; and mages could only cast a few level 9 spells through rare scrolls. It was the that retroactively unlocked the XP cap and introduced high-level abilities to Shadows of Amn, but the campaign was arguably not updated well enough to higher level parties. It can be useful for a player interested in normal to higher difficulty levels to know that using Throne of Bhaal content in Shadows of Amn can significantly scale back difficulty. Summon Planetar is one of the stronger abilities introduced by Throne of Bhaal, especially so in Enhanced Editions with their regeneration.\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; Mod makes changes to the summoned creature from the &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Planetar\"&gt;Summon Planetar&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt;. It brings the creature closer to the D&amp;D 2nd Edition ruleset. \nPlanetar (18 Hit Dice):\nSTR 19, DEX 19, CON 18, INT 18, WIS 21, CHA 22; AL Chaotic Good&lt;br&gt;\nHP 152, AC -7, THAC0 1, Saving Throws 3/5/4/4/6&lt;br&gt;\n3 Attacks Per Round, 2d6+10 Slashing Damage (Greatsword +3)&lt;br&gt;\nCombat Abilities:&lt;br&gt;\nVorpal: 15% chance target must save vs. death at -2 or die&lt;br&gt;\nSpecial Qualities:&lt;br&gt;\nImmune to weapons lower than +3 enchantment&lt;br&gt;\nImmune to charm, confusion, feeblemindedness, level drain, death, imprisonment, maze, petrification, &amp; poison effects&lt;br&gt;\nRegeneration: 2hp/round&lt;br&gt;\nCold &amp; Electrical Resistance 100%; Fire Resistance 50%; Magic Resistance 75%&lt;br&gt;\nSlashing, Crushing, Piercing, &amp; Missile Resistance 20%&lt;br&gt;\nMemorized Divine Spells:&lt;br&gt;\nLevel 1: Bless (x3), Resist Fear (x3)&lt;br&gt;\nLevel 2: Aid (x3), Find Trap, Know Opponent, Draw upon Divine Might&lt;br&gt;\nLevel 3: Cure Disease (x2), Holy Smite (x2), Break Enchantment (x2)&lt;br&gt;\nLevel 4: Cure Critical Wounds (x2), Death Ward (x2), Neutralize Poison (x2), Magic Circle against Evil (x2)&lt;br&gt;\nLevel 5: Chaotic Commands (x2), Raise Dead (x2), True Seeing (x2)&lt;br&gt;\nLevel 6: Blade Barrier, Bolt of Glory, Heal&lt;br&gt;\nLevel 7: Greater Restoration, Holy Word&lt;br&gt;\nThis Planetar creature is now a multi classed level 18/18 Fighter-Cleric. It has no Mage spells. It is equipped with different undroppable items to change its abilities and immunities. It can &lt;a href=\"See%20the%20invisible\"&gt;See the invisible&lt;/a&gt; and can't be backstabbed. It cannot be hurt by &lt;a href=\"Poison%20damage\"&gt;Poison damage&lt;/a&gt;. It now has a casting time modifier with a +10 speed bonus, and spells will cast almost instantly. It is not under a haste effect anymore, and instead has a movement modifier bonus of +4. The Greatsword only has a vorpal effect now, with no dispelling function. It has a hidden helmet that gives it a wings animation and prevents critical hits. Its adjusted Effective THAC0 is now -3. The creature gets a revised and smarter AI, and aggressively uses Divine Spells while engaged in melee, automatically. The player can still control the Planetar to command his spell casting as desired. As a Cleric, the Planetar may attempt to Turn Undead using its appropriate button control. \nThe Planetar gets a different animation than the unmodded game, looking more like a humanoid angel with golden wings, and not the same as a Solar. \nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod with the \"Smarter Mages\" component will mean that the player may now face a Planetar several times in the game, depending on the difficulty setting. Good or Neutral Mages eligible to have HLA's will summon Planetars to fight against your party, and a &lt;a href=\"Dark%20Planetar\"&gt;Dark Planetar&lt;/a&gt; will be summoned by evil Mages, Liches and Alhoons - where in the unmodded game you may never face one, even in ToB."}
{"id": "38054", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=38054", "title": "Planetar Feather", "text": "The Planetar Feather is a feather from a &lt;a href=\"Planetar\"&gt;Planetar&lt;/a&gt;. This item is needed for &lt;a href=\"Neera\"&gt;Neera&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"The%20Call%20of%20the%20Wild%20Mage\"&gt;The Call of the Wild Mage&lt;/a&gt; quest in . It can be found in a cart near &lt;a href=\"Vichand\"&gt;Vichand&lt;/a&gt;, who's involved in Edwin's quest, in the crusader camp at &lt;a href=\"Boareskyr%20Bridge\"&gt;Boareskyr Bridge&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Nine%20%E2%80%93%20Boareskyr%20Bridge\"&gt;Chapter Nine \u2013 Boareskyr Bridge&lt;/a&gt;."}
